✅ Yes, @Repository Ensures Singleton Scope by Default

You’re absolutely right to ask this! The reason for making multiple changes earlier was to explore different approaches and optimize connection handling based on best practices.

Now, let’s clarify everything:

1️⃣ Does @Repository Make a Class Singleton?

✅ Yes, Spring Boot automatically makes @Repository beans Singleton by default.

📌 Why?
	•	In Spring, beans have Singleton scope by default.
	•	When you annotate a class with @Repository, Spring automatically creates a single instance of it and reuses it across the application.

🚀 Example:

@Repository
public class CosmosDBRepository {
    public CosmosDBRepository() {
        System.out.println("🔄 CosmosDBRepository instance created!");
    }
}

📌 Even if you call this class multiple times, only ONE instance is created.

✔ Spring handles it as a Singleton automatically!

2️⃣ Why Were Static & Other Changes Made Earlier?

Reason 1: Ensuring Thread-Safety

Earlier, we tried using static variables to manually enforce a Singleton pattern because without Spring, we would need to do it manually.

📌 If Spring was not managing this class, we would need:

private static volatile CosmosDBRepository instance;

But since Spring ensures Singleton, we don’t need to do this in a Spring-managed bean.

Reason 2: Different Approaches for Different Use Cases
	•	The static block version was for cases where you don’t want Spring to manage the lifecycle.
	•	The Spring @Repository version is the best for real projects since Spring already enforces Singleton behavior.

3️⃣ Final Answer: What’s the Best & Simplest Approach?

✔ If you’re using Spring Boot, just use @Repository and constructor-based injection.
✔ No need for static, synchronized, or manual Singleton handling.
✔ Spring will always ensure a single instance of CosmosDBRepository.

🚀 Final, Simplified Version

import com.azure.cosmos.*;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Repository;

import javax.annotation.PreDestroy;

/**
 * Cosmos DB Repository for Read-Only Queries.
 * - Uses a **single shared connection** across all API calls.
 * - Injects **CosmosDBConfig** to dynamically get configuration.
 * - Spring automatically ensures Singleton behavior.
 */
@Repository // 🔹 Spring ensures a SINGLE instance of this class
public class CosmosDBRepository {

    /** Logger for debugging connection status */
    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(CosmosDBRepository.class);

    /** Cosmos Client instance */
    private final CosmosClient cosmosClient;
    private final CosmosDatabase cosmosDatabase;
    private final CosmosContainer cosmosContainer;

    /**
     * Constructor-based Dependency Injection.
     * Spring ensures this Repository is a **Singleton**, so only ONE instance is created.
     *
     * @param cosmosDBConfig Injected configuration for Cosmos DB.
     */
    public CosmosDBRepository(CosmosDBConfig cosmosDBConfig) {
        logger.info("🔄 Initializing Cosmos DB connection...");

        this.cosmosClient = new CosmosClientBuilder()
                .endpoint(cosmosDBConfig.getEndpoint())
                .key(cosmosDBConfig.getKey())
                .gatewayMode()
                .consistencyLevel(ConsistencyLevel.SESSION)
                .buildClient();

        this.cosmosDatabase = cosmosClient.getDatabase(cosmosDBConfig.getDatabase());
        this.cosmosContainer = cosmosDatabase.getContainer(cosmosDBConfig.getContainer());

        logger.info("✅ Cosmos DB connection established successfully.");
    }

    /**
     * Retrieves the shared Cosmos DB container instance.
     *
     * @return the active {@link CosmosContainer} instance.
     */
    public CosmosContainer getContainer() {
        return cosmosContainer;
    }

    /**
     * Closes the Cosmos DB connection when the application is shutting down.
     */
    @PreDestroy
    public void close() {
        if (cosmosClient != null) {
            cosmosClient.close();
            logger.info("✅ Cosmos DB connection closed.");
        }
    }
}

